author: @KibaSnowpaw
text:
As someone whoâ€™s uploaded over 2,000 videos on a tiny channel, this whole pre-check update hits differently for me mainly because Iâ€™ve never experienced the wave of false strikes bigger creators talk about.

I donâ€™t know if itâ€™s because Iâ€™m small, or because Iâ€™m extremely careful with my editing, but honestly? Every time YouTube demonetizes or restricts one of my videosâ€¦ itâ€™s deserved.
I post borderline content sometimes outfits close to nudity, some very edgy game footage, and the occasional gore-heavy title and YouTube only flags the stuff that should be flagged. Even then, itâ€™s rare unless itâ€™s truly extreme.

What I have noticed is completely different from what this channel describes:
YouTube has never once hit me with a random â€œchild safetyâ€ strike, false community violation, or retroactive punishment. And Iâ€™m a small creator with more uploads than DeepHumor has (heâ€™s around 1,000 videos, Iâ€™m double that), so if the AI was going wild at random, statistically I shouldâ€™ve been nailed a long time ago.

So yeah I agree with him that YouTubeâ€™s AI moderation is messy, slow, inconsistent, and sometimes downright stupid. That part is true. The retroactive checks are the worst.
But from my own experience, I almost feel like smaller channels get scanned differently? Or maybe my content style fits the AIâ€™s â€œsafe zoneâ€ better? I honestly donâ€™t know.

What I do know is this:

â€“ Pre-checks BEFORE uploading is a good idea.
â€“ Not telling us where the violation is has always been the worst part.
â€“ False strikes destroy small channels just as fast as big ones we just donâ€™t get news coverage.
â€“ If YouTube wants creators to improve, timestamps + clear explanations are non-negotiable.
â€“ And relying 100% on AI will ALWAYS lead to mistakes unless they overhaul the system completely.

So yeah, this update is a step in the right directionâ€¦
But until YouTube fixes the part where content passes all checks and STILL gets hit days or months later, nobodyâ€™s really safe big or small.

text: I feel for these parents, I really do, but I donâ€™t know how knowing any extra tormenting details helps them heal.  It would only add to my nightmares and pain. We need a way to connect perpetrators and their families to the pain and suffering of the victims and their families.  The criminal justice system needs to concentrate on SHAME and empathy for rehabilitation and deterrents verses just throwing them in cages and letting them out again.
